You define communication plans for your organization to provide pre-configured plans for major incident communication and collaboration activities. However, in some cases you might need ad hoc communication. For example, you might initiate an ad hoc call with other technical resources, or send an escalation notification that is not in the plan definition to IT executives. These ad hoc communications can be handled by creating a communication plan or task from the Workbench.

false 5e9d3555f9149300964fd82f4d2b2ddd false true For ad hoc communications, you can either create a new communication plan or add a task to an existing communication plan from the Workbench. Click Communications and then click Add. Create a new communication plan or add a task to an existing plan.

Figure 1. Add or create communication plan from the Communications tab

  • When you create a new plan, enter a short description of the communication plan and task, select the channels, set the communication frequency, and add participants. This action adds a new plan to the Workbench and you can send communications using the selected channels.
  • When you create a task for an existing plan, enter a short description of the communication task, select channels, and set the communication frequency. In this case, the participant list is pre-populated based on the selected plan. You can update the participant list by adding or removing participants.

For ad hoc conference calls, you can follow a similar process from the Conference tab on the Workbench. You can create either a new communication plan or add a task to an existing communication plan, but the communication channel is set to Conference.

Figure 2. Add or create communication plan from the Conference tab

You can add and remove recipients for a communication plan by using the Manage Recipients action on the Workbench. This flexibility lets you add additional stakeholders during an incident depending on the situation.

Figure 3. Manage Recipients from the Workbench
